flavorText: The extension and contraction of its muscles generates electricity. It glows when in trouble.
This extremely rare Pokémon is a different color than usual. It is very hard to find.
Living in mud with a high iron content has given it a strong steel body.
What appears to be an iron helmet is actually hardened hair. This Pokémon lives for the thrill of battle.
Minccino greet each other by grooming one another thoroughly with their tails.
The melodies sung by Meloetta have the power to make Pokémon that hear them happy or sad.
It appears in ancient ruins. The pattern on its body doesn't come from any culture in the Galar region, so it remains shrouded in mystery.
They flock around mountains and fields, chasing after bug Pokémon. Their singing is noisy and annoying.
Although it's powerful enough to dig right through volcanic rock, it doesn't allow itself to be seen very often.
There are a hundred or so of them living in Alola's waste-disposal site. They're all hard workers who eat a lot of trash.
Its body is draped in steel armor. It looks heavy, but it can fly at speeds of up to 185 miles an hour!
Possessing a calm demeanor, this Pokémon was revered as a deity incarnate before it was identified as a regional variant of Ninetales.
It is said to have widened the seas by causing downpours. It had been asleep in a marine trench.
It tears and shreds prey with its wickedly sharp scythes. It very rarely spreads its wings to fly.
It spouts poison spores from the top of its head. These spores cause pain all over if inhaled.
It chomps with its gaping mouth. Its huge jaws are actually steel horns that have been transformed.
It lives in forests and fields. Squabbles over territory occur when flocks collide.
Some believe it to be a deity that summons rain clouds. When angered, it lets out a warning cry that rings out like the tolling of a bell.
This is Zygarde when about 10% of its pieces have been assembled. It leaps at its opponent's chest and sinks its sharp fangs into them.
Its metallic whiskers are heavy, so it's not very fast, but it has the power to dig through bedrock.
When it evolves, it sheds the steel carapace that covered its whole body and develops a new one.
There are over a hundred kinds of poison inside its body. Chemical reactions between different poisons are the source of its vitality.
This extremely rare Pokémon is a different color than usual. It is very hard to find.
Once it has identified an enemy, this Pokémon smashes it mercilessly with pincers hard as steel.
Cinccino's body is coated in a special oil that helps it deflect attacks, such as punches.
It discharges electricity from its mane. It creates a thundercloud overhead to drop lightning bolts.
When Staravia evolve into Staraptor, they leave the flock to live alone. They have sturdy wings.
It defends itself by launching spikes, but its aim isn't very good at first. Only after a lot of practice will it improve.
As soon as the tail claws close, its needle tips secrete poison. It can survive a year without food.
It uses three small units to catch prey and battle enemies. The main body mostly just gives orders.
It has the power to control time. It appears in Sinnoh-region myths as an ancient deity.
They're such cowards that they won't hunt alone. When five or so of them get together, they suddenly turn ferocious!
The only thing unlucky about Absol is its appearance. It protects fields and warns people of disaster, so one ought to be grateful for it.
It can learn and speak human words. If they gather, they all learn the same saying.
This Pokémon scrapes its spikes across rocks, and then uses the tips of its feelers to absorb the nutrients it finds within the stone.
They lay their eggs deep inside their nests. When attacked by Heatmor, they retaliate using their massive mandibles.
It habitually shows off its strength with the sparks it creates by ramming its steel body into boulders.
They attack in groups, covering themselves in steel armor to protect themselves from Heatmor.
One kind of Ultra Beast. Witnesses have seen it burn down a forest by expelling gas from its two arms.
Because they are weak individually, they form groups. However, they bicker if the group grows too big.
It usually lives deep in mountains. However, hunger may drive it to eat railroad tracks and cars.
Living in mud with a high iron content has given it a strong steel body.
After shredding its prey, it sharpens its blades on a stone by the river. Each Pawniard has its own favorite sharpening stone.
They will challenge anything, even strong opponents, without fear. Their frequent fights help them become stronger.
While seeking iron for food, it digs tunnels by breaking through bedrock with its steel horns.
Honedge's soul once belonged to a person who was killed a long time ago by the sword that makes up Honedge's body.
It appears as if it is skating on water. It draws prey with a sweet scent from the tip of its head.
It is highly popular among female Trainers for its sublime fur. It does not keep a nest.
It has a body and heart of steel. It worked with its allies to punish people when they hurt Pokémon.
It loves iron ore. Groups of them fight for territory by bashing one another with their steel bodies.
Built roughly 500 years ago by a scientist, the part called the Soul-Heart is the actual life-form.
No matter how strong the Bisharp, it's said that if the blade on its head is chipped, it will retire from its position as the boss.
They fight for their friends without any thought about danger to themselves. One can carry a car while flying.
The shell on its back is made of soil. On a very healthy Turtwig, the shell should feel moist.
One of the legendary bird Pokémon. It is said that its appearance indicates the coming of spring.
A pack of these Pokémon forms to serve a Bisharp boss. Each Pawniard trains diligently, dreaming of one day taking the lead.
Honedge evolves into twins. The two blades rub together to emit a metallic sound that unnerves opponents.
They use shells they've stolen from Shelmet to arm and protect themselves. They're very popular Pokémon in the Galar region.
There are a hundred or so of them living in Alola's waste-disposal site. They're all hard workers who eat a lot of trash.
Usually, its cries are like quiet murmurs. If frightened, it shrieks at the same volume as a jet plane.
The two minigears that compose this Pokémon are closer than twins. They mesh well only with each other.
Violent conflicts erupt between Bisharp and Fraxure over places where sharpening stones can be found.
It claims an entire mountain as its own. The more wounds it has, the more it has battled, so don't take it lightly.
Its body resembles polished metal, and it's both lightweight and strong. The only drawback is that it rusts easily.
Its mechanized body is merely a vessel. Its true self is its Soul-Heart, an artificial soul.
It generates a powerful, freezing energy inside itself, but its body becomes frozen when the energy leaked out.
In this defensive stance, Aegislash uses its steel body and a force field of spectral power to reduce the damage of any attack.
Although it's alien to this world and a danger here, it's apparently a common organism in the world where it normally lives.
Even a robust wrestler will become dizzy and unable to stand when exposed to its 200,000-hertz ultrasonic waves.
This legendary Pokémon can scorch the world with fire. It helps those who want to build a world of truth.
It has a weakness for shiny things. It's been known to sneak into the nests of Gabite—noted collectors of jewels—in search of treasure.
This Pokémon reigns supreme in the skies of the Galar region. The black luster of its steel body could drive terror into the heart of any foe.
When Klang goes all out, the minigear links up perfectly with the outer part of the big gear, and this Pokémon's rotation speed increases sharply.
It's hypothesized that it's monitoring those those who destroy the ecosystem from deep in the cave where it lives.
It can telepathically communicate with people. It changes its appearance using its down that refracts light.
It has a weakness for shiny things. It's been known to sneak into the nests of Gabite—noted collectors of jewels—in search of treasure.
Even a robust wrestler will become dizzy and unable to stand when exposed to its 200,000-hertz ultrasonic waves.
It glides on its outstretched membrane while shocking foes with the electricity stored in the pouches on its cheeks.
It has the ability to alter the composition of its body to suit its surrounding environment.
After fleeing a volcanic eruption, it ended up moving to an area of snowy mountains. Its ice shell is as hard as steel.
It concentrates its mental energy and fires off mysterious waves called auras, which can crush boulders of large size to dust.
It checks its surroundings and location using reflections of the ultrasonic waves from its mouth.
